1
00:00:15,098 --> 00:00:16,599
Next, please.

2
00:00:17,184 --> 00:00:18,559
Come on, come on.

3
00:00:19,019 --> 00:00:20,186
Next.

4
00:00:20,562 --> 00:00:21,687
Name.

5
00:00:21,855 --> 00:00:23,564
Gus Gorman.

6
00:00:31,365 --> 00:00:33,699
Ah, yes. August Gorman.

7
00:00:33,867 --> 00:00:36,160
Have you looked for work this week?

8
00:00:36,703 --> 00:00:39,080
- Yes.
- What kind?

9
00:00:41,333 --> 00:00:44,210
- Kitchen technician.
- Dishwasher. Any luck?

10
00:00:45,087 --> 00:00:46,128
No, but...

11
00:00:46,296 --> 00:00:50,007
Mr. Gorman, according to our records,
you've been unemployed for 36 weeks.

12
00:00:50,217 --> 00:00:51,342
No, it's 35.

13
00:00:51,510 --> 00:00:53,386
Not counting this week.

14
00:00:53,637 --> 00:00:58,015
You secured employment in June as
a messenger and were discharged after...

15
00:00:58,183 --> 00:01:00,977
- one day for losing...
- No, they said I lost it.

16
00:01:01,186 --> 00:01:04,230
I did not lose it!
It was stolen by a pickpocket.

17
00:01:04,398 --> 00:01:05,856
A television set?

18
00:01:06,108 --> 00:01:09,735
It was a teeny-tiny, teeny-weensy
Japanese television set.

19
00:01:09,903 --> 00:01:14,865
The other employment you found
was in a fast-food joint, which lasted...

20
00:01:15,075 --> 00:01:16,409
28 minutes?

21
00:01:16,910 --> 00:01:19,245
That's some kind of record.
Talk about fast.

22
00:01:19,496 --> 00:01:24,000
Those people are crazy. They expect
you to learn that stuff in one day.

23
00:01:24,209 --> 00:01:28,170
"Hold the lettuce. Hold the ketchup.
Can I have some sauce, please?"

24
00:01:28,380 --> 00:01:30,923
- Mr. Gorman...
- "Two buns. No buns. Some cheese".

25
00:01:31,258 --> 00:01:34,635
Mr. Gorman, the city of Metropolis
is generous to a fault, but...

26
00:01:34,928 --> 00:01:36,012
I'm not the fault!

27
00:01:36,179 --> 00:01:38,097
Thirty-six weeks
of chronic unemployment.

28
00:01:38,265 --> 00:01:41,434
Thirty-six weeks of living off the taxes
of hard-working citizens.

29
00:01:41,643 --> 00:01:44,895
- Do you know what you are?
- Don't call me a bum, I'm not a bum!

30
00:01:45,856 --> 00:01:50,735
You are, I was about to say,
no longer eligible.

31
00:01:51,361 --> 00:01:52,778
- Well, look...
- Next.

32
00:01:52,946 --> 00:01:55,072
Wait. What about this week?
I need this week!

33
00:01:55,449 --> 00:01:56,532
Next.

34
00:01:56,867 --> 00:01:58,451
You mean, that's it?

35
00:01:58,785 --> 00:02:00,661
"Finished," like "over"?

36
00:02:04,541 --> 00:02:05,666
Next.

37
00:02:06,293 --> 00:02:08,169
"Next" as in "bye".

38
00:02:08,920 --> 00:02:10,171
Next!

39
00:02:13,175 --> 00:02:14,258
Name.

40
00:02:15,969 --> 00:02:17,970
Excuse me, brother,
can I have a light?

41
00:02:48,627 --> 00:02:50,836
- How you doing, Alex?
- Hi, Jimmy.

42
00:03:50,021 --> 00:03:52,022
Huh? Ah.

43
00:04:48,622 --> 00:04:49,830
Excuse me.

44
00:06:05,115 --> 00:06:06,532
Say thank you.

45
00:06:06,700 --> 00:06:08,284
Wow!

46
00:06:25,552 --> 00:06:27,886
Way to go, Superman!

47
00:07:43,630 --> 00:07:45,798
Your drink is on its way.

48
00:07:47,300 --> 00:07:48,467
Sir.

49
00:07:48,635 --> 00:07:50,219
Excuse me...

50
00:07:52,222 --> 00:07:56,934
but what if you wanna program two
bilateral coordinates at the same time?

51
00:07:57,143 --> 00:07:59,144
You can't do that. It's impossible.

52
00:07:59,312 --> 00:08:01,063
- But if you can't...
- Oh, no.

53
00:08:01,272 --> 00:08:05,317
Computer technology is very advanced,
young lady, but it can't do that.

54
00:08:05,527 --> 00:08:08,487
But if you think we can't
do it that way, what happens?

55
00:08:08,655 --> 00:08:10,280
Sir.

56
00:08:15,495 --> 00:08:16,829
Good Lord.

57
00:08:17,414 --> 00:08:18,831
How did you do that?

58
00:08:19,040 --> 00:08:22,626
I don't know. I just did it.

59
00:08:41,646 --> 00:08:44,148
- Who's this?
- That's him, Ross Webster.

60
00:08:44,357 --> 00:08:47,359
Just after he received the award for
Humanitarian of the Year.

61
00:08:47,527 --> 00:08:49,278
He is good-looking.

62
00:08:49,487 --> 00:08:51,363
Because I gave him F2 at a 50th.

63
00:08:51,614 --> 00:08:53,365
One thing I don't understand...

64
00:08:53,575 --> 00:08:57,870
the point of the story Lois wrote
is how Ross got this great honor...

65
00:08:58,037 --> 00:09:01,707
and you bring me one picture of him
and 15 pictures of this other person.

66
00:09:01,875 --> 00:09:04,543
- Who is she?
- Lorelei Ambrosia. She's Webster's...

67
00:09:04,711 --> 00:09:07,379
She's just Webster's.
Let's leave it at that.

68
00:09:07,589 --> 00:09:10,215
- Who's this other woman?
- His sister, Vera Webster.

69
00:09:10,383 --> 00:09:11,717
- Picture looks fuzzy.
- What?

70
00:09:11,885 --> 00:09:15,679
The picture's fine, chief.
She looks like that in real life.

71
00:09:16,222 --> 00:09:20,100
- She's VP of Webscoe Industries.
- I really don't understand you.

72
00:09:20,310 --> 00:09:23,604
A boring banquet and you bring me
3000 boring pictures.

73
00:09:23,813 --> 00:09:26,565
Yet Superman saves a man
from drowning on Third Avenue...

74
00:09:26,733 --> 00:09:30,152
while you just stand there and
you don't bring me one picture!

75
00:09:30,320 --> 00:09:32,154
Chief, I didn't have
my camera with me.

76
00:09:32,363 --> 00:09:36,742
A photographer eats with his camera.
A photographer sleeps with his camera.

77
00:09:36,910 --> 00:09:39,369
- I'm glad I'm a writer.
- Mr. White, please.

78
00:09:39,579 --> 00:09:42,748
It's time for you to draw this month's
winning JINGO number.

79
00:09:42,916 --> 00:09:45,501
Prize is an all-expenses trip
to South America.

80
00:09:45,668 --> 00:09:48,504
- I don't know why the idiot in Circulation...
- Good morning.

81
00:09:48,671 --> 00:09:50,714
- Hi, Clark.
- Hi, Lois. Morning, Jimmy.

82
00:09:50,924 --> 00:09:52,674
You've got mustard on your lapel.

83
00:09:52,884 --> 00:09:54,885
Excuse me, Mr. White,
I hate to interrupt...

84
00:09:55,094 --> 00:09:57,346
Sorry. I'm busy.
I got a paper to get out here.

85
00:09:57,555 --> 00:09:59,598
It'll never replace the printing press.

86
00:09:59,766 --> 00:10:02,768
- What's the number, Mr. White?
- Fifty-three.

87
00:10:04,270 --> 00:10:06,939
- Mr. White...
- Fifty-three!

88
00:10:07,565 --> 00:10:10,609
- Mr. White...
- You've got to pull three more numbers.

89
00:10:10,777 --> 00:10:13,570
I promised I'd call them back today.
What do you think?

90
00:10:14,113 --> 00:10:17,783
- Well, I don't know, Kent...
- I think it'd make a terrific story.

91
00:10:18,952 --> 00:10:20,619
What's a terrific story?

92
00:10:20,787 --> 00:10:23,163
Kent's been invited
to his high-school reunion.

93
00:10:23,623 --> 00:10:25,123
- Say.
- Yeah.

94
00:10:25,291 --> 00:10:27,125
Could we have the next number?

95
00:10:27,293 --> 00:10:29,795
It's practically an
American institution. Isn't it?

96
00:10:29,963 --> 00:10:33,924
I don't know, Mr. Kent. Most of
the people I know are still in high school.

97
00:10:37,470 --> 00:10:38,554
Thirty-three.

98
00:10:38,721 --> 00:10:41,473
What I thought this story
would be about, Mr. White, is...

99
00:10:41,683 --> 00:10:43,308
Thirty-three.

100
00:10:43,810 --> 00:10:47,312
Is how much the typical small town
has changed in the last 15 years.

101
00:10:47,564 --> 00:10:48,689
Take me, for example:

102
00:10:48,898 --> 00:10:52,568
Can I really go back to middle America
now as a Metropolis sophisticate?

103
00:10:52,735 --> 00:10:55,737
I'm really excited about this.
In fact, I was looking around...

104
00:10:55,947 --> 00:10:58,407
in my closet last night...

105
00:10:58,616 --> 00:11:02,452
and I even found
my old high-school sweater.

106
00:11:04,747 --> 00:11:06,832
- Smallville.
- Mr. White.

107
00:11:07,500 --> 00:11:09,501
Can I go ahead
and make my travel plan?

108
00:11:09,711 --> 00:11:11,211
Same question about mine.

109
00:11:12,088 --> 00:11:15,841
Tell your people the prodigal son
and his photographer are coming home.

110
00:11:16,009 --> 00:11:17,843
Oh, gee, thanks, Mr. White.

111
00:11:19,762 --> 00:11:23,015
It isn't easy for me to lose
one of my best reporters.

112
00:11:23,224 --> 00:11:25,601
- That's okay.
- You deserve the vacation, Lois.

113
00:11:25,810 --> 00:11:27,019
Thank you.

114
00:11:29,689 --> 00:11:31,148
Lois, are you going someplace?

115
00:11:32,358 --> 00:11:36,028
Clark, you know some people
get to go all the way to Smallville...

116
00:11:36,195 --> 00:11:39,990
and then there are others of us
who have to go to Bermuda.

117
00:11:40,491 --> 00:11:41,825
Golly.

118
00:11:42,035 --> 00:11:43,368
- Bye.
- Bye, Miss Lane.

119
00:11:44,871 --> 00:11:48,874
- Have fun.
- Mr. White, the next number, please.

120
00:11:49,042 --> 00:11:52,044
Well, I guess I better be going too.

121
00:11:54,005 --> 00:11:55,672
So I'll be going.

122
00:11:58,801 --> 00:12:00,135
Bye.

123
00:12:02,555 --> 00:12:04,723
Couldn't we get a computer to do this?

124
00:12:28,081 --> 00:12:30,791
- Hey, what is this?
- First paycheck.

125
00:12:31,209 --> 00:12:35,420
This is the first rip-off, man! We're
supposed to get 225 a week, right?

126
00:12:35,588 --> 00:12:38,882
This says, "$143.80".
How am I supposed to live on that?

127
00:12:39,092 --> 00:12:42,386
State tax, federal tax,
social security tax...

128
00:12:42,553 --> 00:12:45,222
It's so you're still getting
some money when you hit 65.

129
00:12:45,390 --> 00:12:47,599
So I'm getting money when I? 65?

130
00:12:47,850 --> 00:12:49,101
I want mine now!

131
00:12:49,310 --> 00:12:53,814
I want to enjoy it while I'm young.
I wanna get up and get down. Boogie.

132
00:12:55,316 --> 00:13:00,112
Actually, it's probably more like
$143.80 and one half cent.

133
00:13:00,321 --> 00:13:04,616
There are always fractions left over,
but big corporations round it down.

134
00:13:04,867 --> 00:13:07,619
What do I do with half a cent?
Buy a thoroughbred mouse?

135
00:13:07,829 --> 00:13:09,621
Everybody loses those fractions?

136
00:13:09,872 --> 00:13:12,624
They don't lose them.
You can't lose what you never got.

137
00:13:12,875 --> 00:13:15,043
Then what happens?
The company gets them?

138
00:13:15,253 --> 00:13:19,881
They can't be bothered collecting that
from your paycheck any more than you.

139
00:13:20,133 --> 00:13:21,466
Then what happens to them?

140
00:13:21,759 --> 00:13:26,221
Well, they're just floating around out there.
The computers know where.

141
00:13:26,431 --> 00:13:27,931
How many sugars?

142
00:13:28,641 --> 00:13:29,975
One and a half.

143
00:13:37,358 --> 00:13:39,109
It's quitting time, Gus. You coming?

144
00:13:39,277 --> 00:13:43,947
Yeah. No, actually, I got some
stuff to finish up, so...

145
00:13:44,157 --> 00:13:48,994
Working overtime, huh? What are you
doing, buddy? Looking for a raise?

146
00:13:49,787 --> 00:13:52,164
Yeah, looking for a raise.

147
00:14:29,660 --> 00:14:30,702
You bet.

148
00:14:36,834 --> 00:14:40,545
But my Uncle Al on my father's
side, he won't eat her stuffing.

149
00:14:40,713 --> 00:14:45,383
He says it should be cooked on the outside.
She cooks it on the inside.

150
00:14:45,551 --> 00:14:48,720
My mother told my Aunt Helen.
She's my father's half sister.

151
00:14:48,888 --> 00:14:51,056
- I told you that, right?
- Yeah.

152
00:14:51,224 --> 00:14:52,933
- And anyway, the family...
- Hey, hey.

153
00:14:53,351 --> 00:14:55,227
- Look at that.
- Wow.

154
00:15:06,072 --> 00:15:10,408
Okay, your choice.
You can turn back or pull over till it's over.

155
00:15:10,576 --> 00:15:13,161
- How long will it take?
- Can't tell with these fires.

156
00:15:13,329 --> 00:15:16,414
I mean, that fire...
That's spreading like wildfire.

157
00:15:16,582 --> 00:15:18,083
It's just a building burning.

158
00:15:18,251 --> 00:15:20,585
It's not just a building.
That's a chemical plant.

159
00:15:21,087 --> 00:15:24,381
You know what I mean.
It's like... It's like chemicals.

160
00:15:24,590 --> 00:15:29,219
If any of that stuff goes up in smoke,
we're in for a hairy time around here.

161
00:15:31,097 --> 00:15:32,222
- Clark.
- Yeah?

162
00:15:32,390 --> 00:15:34,599
I want you to keep
these people distracted.

163
00:15:34,767 --> 00:15:35,934
What are you doing?

164
00:15:36,102 --> 00:15:39,229
What am I doing?
Remember what the chief said?

165
00:15:39,397 --> 00:15:41,606
A photographer always
goes after a story.

166
00:15:41,774 --> 00:15:43,358
That could be dangerous, Jimmy.

167
00:15:43,568 --> 00:15:47,612
Danger goes with the territory,
Mr. Kent.

168
00:16:24,150 --> 00:16:27,402
Help me!

169
00:16:31,324 --> 00:16:33,658
- How can I help?
- Get this man a helmet.

170
00:16:33,826 --> 00:16:36,036
- It's you. Forget the helmet.
- How bad is it?

171
00:16:36,245 --> 00:16:40,624
My God, it's a nightmare. Everything's
either explosive or flammable or worse.

172
00:16:44,837 --> 00:16:46,254
Get the ladder truck in here.

173
00:16:46,422 --> 00:16:49,299
- It won't reach.
- My God, they're trapped!

174
00:16:50,051 --> 00:16:52,844
What's he gonna do?
Fly them down one at a time?

175
00:17:11,072 --> 00:17:13,198
Let's go! Everybody,
down there! Move it!

176
00:17:13,449 --> 00:17:15,033
Come on! Hurry up!

177
00:17:15,201 --> 00:17:16,326
There you go.

178
00:17:20,206 --> 00:17:22,082
Right down there. Take it easy.

179
00:17:24,335 --> 00:17:26,169
All right. Everybody down there!

180
00:17:28,214 --> 00:17:29,547
Keep moving!

181
00:18:02,748 --> 00:18:04,916
Sir, get out. I'll show you
the quickest way.

182
00:18:05,126 --> 00:18:07,252
Go on. Look after the others.
I can't leave.

183
00:18:07,420 --> 00:18:09,671
- Why not?
- I gotta stay and look after those.

184
00:18:09,880 --> 00:18:11,423
That's concentrated Beltric acid.

185
00:18:11,632 --> 00:18:14,718
If that stuff heats up over 180 degrees,
we've got a crisis...

186
00:18:14,927 --> 00:18:17,262
that'll make this fire
look like a picnic.

187
00:18:17,430 --> 00:18:18,513
What does it do?

188
00:18:18,764 --> 00:18:21,558
As long as it remains stable,
it's just ordinary acid.

189
00:18:21,934 --> 00:18:25,228
But if it begins to heat up,
it'll turn volatile.

190
00:18:25,438 --> 00:18:28,648
You'll get a great cloud of smoke
that will eat through anything.

191
00:18:28,858 --> 00:18:31,443
Steel, concrete, anything.

192
00:18:42,872 --> 00:18:44,080
Who the hell is that?

193
00:18:44,248 --> 00:18:49,085
- Hey, you! Get off of there!
- I'm just gonna get a couple more shots.

194
00:18:56,594 --> 00:18:59,387
Ow! Ah!

195
00:19:05,311 --> 00:19:08,688
Tell them to bring their hoses
back here! Quickly!

196
00:19:11,692 --> 00:19:12,776
Help!

197
00:19:13,611 --> 00:19:16,112
Help! Help me!

198
00:19:17,948 --> 00:19:21,451
Help! Somebody help me!

199
00:19:22,411 --> 00:19:23,995
- Help!
- It's all right.

200
00:19:24,246 --> 00:19:26,831
- Superman! My leg.
- I got you. Take it easy.

201
00:19:26,999 --> 00:19:28,792
All right. We'll go nice and easy.

202
00:19:29,001 --> 00:19:32,796
Okay, I'm sorry.
All right? Here we go.

203
00:19:36,342 --> 00:19:38,843
Medics! Over here, please.

204
00:19:39,470 --> 00:19:41,638
That's it. Here you go.

205
00:19:41,806 --> 00:19:43,348
Go easy. It's the left leg.

206
00:19:44,809 --> 00:19:46,184
- My camera.
- Yeah.

207
00:19:47,645 --> 00:19:49,729
It's a clean break right across the fibula.

208
00:19:50,272 --> 00:19:53,817
- My camera.
- Sorry, Jimmy. You'll be okay.

209
00:19:55,319 --> 00:19:59,739
Get that fire out, otherwise there'll be an
acid cloud all over the Eastern seaboard.

210
00:20:03,828 --> 00:20:06,371
- The pump house is gone!
- What?

211
00:20:06,539 --> 00:20:09,040
- The pump house!
- We've lost the water pressure!

212
00:20:10,751 --> 00:20:12,544
- We've got to have water!
- How?

213
00:20:12,711 --> 00:20:15,713
Lake Comooga's five miles from here.
We'd need a five-mile hose!

214
00:20:15,881 --> 00:20:17,882
- Where's this lake?
- That way.

215
00:20:26,517 --> 00:20:27,684
Tell them it's hopeless.

216
00:20:27,852 --> 00:20:30,270
You told me we had
an adequate water supply.

217
00:21:31,457 --> 00:21:32,457
Water!

218
00:21:47,640 --> 00:21:49,641
I tell you, that man's a miracle!

219
00:22:15,501 --> 00:22:18,002
Carol, you got gorgeous!

220
00:22:29,515 --> 00:22:31,140
Look at you.

221
00:22:39,441 --> 00:22:42,652
That was against Mid-City.
I'll never forget it.

222
00:22:44,029 --> 00:22:45,822
Fourth quarter, score was tied...

223
00:22:46,490 --> 00:22:48,700
we're back at the 25-yard line.

224
00:22:48,993 --> 00:22:52,203
Coach sends in a play,
Right Flanker Option.

225
00:23:02,131 --> 00:23:04,340
You really have grown, Clark.

226
00:23:04,508 --> 00:23:06,384
You look very well, Miss Bannister.

227
00:23:06,552 --> 00:23:11,347
I can't complain. I take the stairs
a little slow and I have these spells.

228
00:23:12,141 --> 00:23:14,058
But really, I can't complain.

229
00:23:14,977 --> 00:23:16,019
Lana?

230
00:23:17,187 --> 00:23:18,229
Clark?

231
00:23:23,819 --> 00:23:27,405
Would you excuse me? There's someone
I'd really like to say hello to.

232
00:23:30,743 --> 00:23:31,993
Lana?

233
00:23:33,370 --> 00:23:36,539
- Lana Lang? It's great to see you.
- Clark.

234
00:23:37,875 --> 00:23:41,252
- You look wonderful.
- Me? No, you look...

235
00:23:41,462 --> 00:23:44,464
- Let me give you a hand with that.
- No, no. I can manage.

236
00:23:45,174 --> 00:23:46,591
Uh...

237
00:23:47,968 --> 00:23:51,220
This is the first time you've come back
since your mom passed away.

238
00:23:51,430 --> 00:23:53,264
Yeah. I'm sorry.

239
00:23:56,268 --> 00:23:57,435
I heard that you and...

240
00:23:58,395 --> 00:24:00,730
- Donald split up.
- Did you eat yet?

241
00:24:00,939 --> 00:24:01,981
No.

242
00:24:02,274 --> 00:24:04,984
Beg your pardon. Excuse me. Sorry.

243
00:24:08,781 --> 00:24:10,615
- That's not right.
- No?

244
00:24:10,783 --> 00:24:13,284
You're right about Donald and me,
but... Hold this, okay?

245
00:24:13,494 --> 00:24:14,869
Oh, sure.

246
00:24:17,289 --> 00:24:18,790
Hi, Kent.

247
00:24:19,124 --> 00:24:21,417
Hi. How you doing?

248
00:24:22,628 --> 00:24:24,921
I'm sorry. I'm going nuts. Thanks.

249
00:24:28,801 --> 00:24:30,760
- Clark.
- Yeah.

250
00:24:31,637 --> 00:24:33,137
Lana.

251
00:24:33,639 --> 00:24:35,807
Uh-oh. Um...

252
00:24:36,141 --> 00:24:37,308
Hey, sweet.

253
00:24:37,643 --> 00:24:38,810
Here I am.

254
00:24:40,020 --> 00:24:44,148
Remember when you were prom queen?
All these guys were waiting for a dance?

255
00:24:44,316 --> 00:24:46,984
There's only one guy on your
dance card now. Huh, honey?

256
00:24:47,152 --> 00:24:49,028
- That's good old...
- Brad Wilson.

257
00:24:49,613 --> 00:24:52,073
- Hi, Brad.
- Hi, Kent.

258
00:24:52,408 --> 00:24:54,158
Long time no see.

259
00:24:54,326 --> 00:24:56,244
You know, see, see, see?

260
00:24:56,912 --> 00:24:59,455
- Come on, Lana.
- No, I can't.

261
00:24:59,832 --> 00:25:01,791
- Clark already asked me.
- I did?

262
00:25:01,959 --> 00:25:03,793
- Yeah.
- Oh, excuse me.

263
00:25:04,920 --> 00:25:06,796
Lana, I haven't danced...

264
00:25:51,592 --> 00:25:54,385
Ah, Gorman.
Another week, another check.

265
00:25:57,306 --> 00:26:01,225
Don't you have another one for me?
I put in a voucher for expenses.

266
00:26:01,393 --> 00:26:02,727
What?

267
00:26:06,064 --> 00:26:07,106
Yeah, yeah.

268
00:26:07,399 --> 00:26:08,608
Here you go.

269
00:26:19,995 --> 00:26:21,579
Ooo...

270
00:26:31,256 --> 00:26:33,007
Thanks for helping me out.

271
00:26:33,342 --> 00:26:35,927
You kidding? A lot of guys
would like to be where I am.

272
00:26:36,136 --> 00:26:38,554
You'd be surprised at how many
offers I didn't get.

273
00:26:38,722 --> 00:26:40,431
Even Brad wouldn't stick around.

274
00:26:40,641 --> 00:26:42,099
It really isn't easy.

275
00:26:42,267 --> 00:26:44,268
The streamers?
Yeah, you just pull, and...

276
00:26:44,436 --> 00:26:46,938
No, not the streamers. Everything.

277
00:26:47,147 --> 00:26:49,440
Not that I'm complaining.
It's just that...

278
00:26:49,691 --> 00:26:52,610
I don't know why,
I just feel like I can talk to you.

279
00:26:52,778 --> 00:26:53,903
What?

280
00:26:54,071 --> 00:26:56,405
I feel like I can talk to you!

281
00:26:57,366 --> 00:26:58,950
- You can?
- Yes.

282
00:26:59,159 --> 00:27:01,118
- You know something, Lana?
- What?

283
00:27:03,163 --> 00:27:04,455
I always...

284
00:27:05,249 --> 00:27:06,958
I always wished that you would.

285
00:27:07,167 --> 00:27:09,126
I mean, even back in high school.

286
00:27:09,294 --> 00:27:11,963
- Remember when you were?
- Queen of the prom.

287
00:27:12,548 --> 00:27:15,591
Then three years after the royal wedding,
the king abdicated.

288
00:27:15,801 --> 00:27:17,969
- Isn't that terrible?
- Yeah, sure is.

289
00:27:18,136 --> 00:27:21,973
There must be a gallon
of potato salad left over.

290
00:27:22,599 --> 00:27:24,475
You know what the problem is?

291
00:27:25,602 --> 00:27:27,478
I don't know, too much mayonnaise?

292
00:27:27,688 --> 00:27:30,439
Donald loved mayonnaise.
Why would that be the problem?

293
00:27:30,649 --> 00:27:33,484
No, the problem is,
why do I stay in Smallville?

294
00:27:33,694 --> 00:27:35,444
Believe me, I've asked myself that.

295
00:27:35,696 --> 00:27:40,157
Do you know how lucky you are
to live in Metropolis? The Big Apricot.

296
00:27:40,325 --> 00:27:41,576
Well, Lana, you could...

297
00:27:41,743 --> 00:27:44,495
Easy to say. But how?
What about Ricky?

298
00:27:44,746 --> 00:27:47,081
- Ricky?
- My little boy.

299
00:27:47,499 --> 00:27:49,625
- You? Oh, that's great.
- Yeah.

300
00:27:49,835 --> 00:27:54,338
I mean, at least here we have a house
and I've got a job that pays the bills.

301
00:27:54,506 --> 00:27:58,009
Except for last winter when
the fuel bills kept going up and up.

302
00:27:58,719 --> 00:28:01,512
Yeah. Even had to pawn
my diamond ring then.

303
00:28:01,847 --> 00:28:03,139
That's a shame.

304
00:28:10,856 --> 00:28:12,523
You never got married?

305
00:28:14,610 --> 00:28:16,235
- Me?
- Yeah.

306
00:28:16,737 --> 00:28:18,195
Well, I was...

307
00:28:19,656 --> 00:28:21,198
No. Not...

308
00:28:30,375 --> 00:28:33,252
You know, years later you can
look at someone and think...

309
00:28:33,503 --> 00:28:36,255
"Well, I guess that's
the one that got away".

310
00:28:41,136 --> 00:28:44,722
Give me that again, old buddy.
Run it by me just one more time.

311
00:28:44,890 --> 00:28:47,391
- Eighty-five thousand dollars.
- Missing?

312
00:28:47,559 --> 00:28:51,145
Embezzled, Mr. Webster.
Stolen from the firm.

313
00:28:51,355 --> 00:28:52,563
By whom?

314
00:28:52,773 --> 00:28:55,274
That's what I want to know.
By whom? Whom?

315
00:28:55,484 --> 00:28:57,068
Vera, get ahold of yourself.

316
00:28:57,986 --> 00:28:59,362
Nobody else ever will.

317
00:29:00,072 --> 00:29:01,238
I don't know.

318
00:29:01,406 --> 00:29:02,406
Whom?

319
00:29:02,574 --> 00:29:04,742
In the old days it was simple.

320
00:29:04,910 --> 00:29:09,288
We kept books, we knew what was
going in and what was paid out.

321
00:29:09,498 --> 00:29:11,165
If somebody wanted to rob you...

322
00:29:11,333 --> 00:29:13,876
they'd come in with a gun and say,
"Stick them up".

323
00:29:14,086 --> 00:29:17,213
Now they get blasted computers
to do their dirty work.

324
00:29:17,798 --> 00:29:20,675
My old friend, you are yesterday.

325
00:29:20,884 --> 00:29:23,761
Whoever pulled this caper is tomorrow.

326
00:29:25,889 --> 00:29:28,057
Mr. Webster,
it's time for your massage.

327
00:29:28,225 --> 00:29:30,101
Does this woman
have the right to burst in?

328
00:29:30,310 --> 00:29:33,896
Now, now, Vera. Simpson,
you know my psychic nutritionist?

329
00:29:34,106 --> 00:29:38,234
- Hello.
- We are trying to hold a meeting here.

330
00:29:38,402 --> 00:29:42,446
Why don't you hold your breath instead.
Maybe you'll turn blue.

331
00:29:42,614 --> 00:29:45,950
- Improvement.
- I'm about to take a human life.

332
00:29:46,118 --> 00:29:49,328
Simpson, would you excuse us
for a second, please?

333
00:29:52,916 --> 00:29:55,960
- Mouths closed. Ears open.
- She's a big pig.

334
00:29:56,128 --> 00:29:59,255
I can't have anyone with me
who isn't with me.

335
00:29:59,589 --> 00:30:00,965
Now, girls.

336
00:30:01,425 --> 00:30:02,925
Simpson.

337
00:30:03,260 --> 00:30:04,635
Well, old chum. What now?

338
00:30:04,886 --> 00:30:07,596
Kiss the 85 thou goodbye?

339
00:30:07,806 --> 00:30:11,600
Keep on paying the thief his salary
until he shakes the money tree again?

340
00:30:11,810 --> 00:30:14,895
- He's bound to slip up sooner or later.
- Why?

341
00:30:15,105 --> 00:30:17,440
That's what they always say
in the movies.

342
00:30:17,649 --> 00:30:20,151
He won't slip up at all. No, not at all.

343
00:30:20,360 --> 00:30:22,987
He'll keep quietly taking
the bread from our mouths.

344
00:30:23,155 --> 00:30:27,408
He'll keep a low profile and won't
do a thing to call attention to himself.

345
00:30:27,617 --> 00:30:31,996
Unless, of course, he is
a complete and utter moron.

346
00:30:49,639 --> 00:30:51,390
I'll go first. Andrew.

347
00:30:51,600 --> 00:30:55,019
- I'll pick Chris.
- You feel good? You feel ready?

348
00:30:55,270 --> 00:30:56,520
LANA Ricky, your shoe.

349
00:30:56,688 --> 00:31:00,024
- You mean, we've gotta take Ricky?
- You guys lost the toss.

350
00:31:00,192 --> 00:31:02,359
All right, come on, Ricky.

351
00:31:02,527 --> 00:31:04,528
- Wait, wait...
- Come on, good luck.

352
00:31:05,655 --> 00:31:08,491
- I just can't stand this.
- Oh, Lana. It'll be okay.

353
00:31:08,700 --> 00:31:10,993
I know, I was a late bloomer myself.

354
00:31:11,203 --> 00:31:15,873
It's not just that he's small, he's
the only kid in town without a father.

355
00:31:16,291 --> 00:31:20,628
Oh, look. He's stewed to the gills
in the middle of the afternoon.

356
00:31:20,796 --> 00:31:23,005
- Gee, all he had was chocolate milk.
- No, him.

357
00:31:23,215 --> 00:31:24,673
Hey, sweet thing.

358
00:31:25,133 --> 00:31:27,051
Little kid getting hassled, huh?

359
00:31:27,719 --> 00:31:30,221
- Kent, you still here?
- I seem to be, Brad.

360
00:31:30,430 --> 00:31:33,140
All he needs is a few pointers
from the old champ here.

361
00:31:33,517 --> 00:31:36,185
I won the all-country bowling
trophy two years in a row.

362
00:31:36,353 --> 00:31:37,394
I didn't know that.

363
00:31:37,562 --> 00:31:39,522
Yeah. Natural athlete
can play any sport.

364
00:31:39,689 --> 00:31:41,482
Brad, you're just gonna
make it worse.

365
00:31:41,650 --> 00:31:44,151
- It's all right. It'll be okay.
- He'll make it worse.

366
00:31:50,492 --> 00:31:52,493
You watch, he'll get a spare.

367
00:31:52,744 --> 00:31:54,203
Come on, Ricky.

368
00:31:55,580 --> 00:31:57,456
Hey, kid, you're holding it all wrong.

369
00:31:58,041 --> 00:32:01,335
- Let old Brad show you how it's done.
- Brad.

370
00:32:02,254 --> 00:32:06,257
Excuse me. Say, Brad, I think maybe
he'll be better off doing it his way.

371
00:32:06,508 --> 00:32:10,052
For a guy lucky to be waterboy,
you've got a big mouth.

372
00:32:10,470 --> 00:32:13,514
I don't think he needs a lesson
in front of the other kids.

373
00:32:13,723 --> 00:32:17,601
- He needs a man to show him.
- He's doing just fine. Excuse me.

374
00:32:19,479 --> 00:32:20,771
Here you go, Ricky.

375
00:32:20,981 --> 00:32:23,983
And give it your best shot.
Okay? There you go.

376
00:32:26,403 --> 00:32:27,611
Sorry.

377
00:32:34,119 --> 00:32:35,286
Ah-choo!

378
00:32:43,712 --> 00:32:45,129
Gesundheit.

379
00:32:45,297 --> 00:32:46,463
Thank you.

380
00:32:49,509 --> 00:32:51,760
Hey, Gus, the boss wants to see you.

381
00:32:51,970 --> 00:32:54,513
He can see me all right.
Hello, Mr. Lewis.

382
00:32:54,723 --> 00:32:58,142
No, not that boss. The boss.

383
00:32:59,311 --> 00:33:00,811
- You mean, the boss...
- Yup.

384
00:33:01,021 --> 00:33:02,479
- Wants to see me?
- Yup.

385
00:33:02,647 --> 00:33:05,816
Oh, my God,
why would he wanna see me?

386
00:33:06,026 --> 00:33:07,151
I mean...

387
00:33:08,486 --> 00:33:10,821
Why would the boss wanna see me?

388
00:33:12,073 --> 00:33:13,741
There's no reason.

389
00:33:15,035 --> 00:33:16,535
Then why'd he? Oh, I know!

390
00:33:16,745 --> 00:33:19,830
It's my suggestion
for the volleyball uniforms.

391
00:33:20,040 --> 00:33:21,248
That's it.

392
00:33:33,845 --> 00:33:37,056
Ross the boss.
Ross the boss. The boss!

393
00:33:37,974 --> 00:33:40,059
Be calm. Be cool. Be collected.

394
00:33:44,773 --> 00:33:47,775
Mr. Webster? Mr. Webster?

395
00:33:48,318 --> 00:33:51,612
Mr. Webster, I did not... Mr. Webster.

396
00:33:52,030 --> 00:33:54,031
Mr. August Gorman?

397
00:33:54,199 --> 00:33:55,449
August Gorman here.

398
00:33:55,659 --> 00:34:00,204
I know you're a man of compassion,
and I don't wanna go to jail...

399
00:34:00,372 --> 00:34:02,373
because they have robbers
and rapists...

400
00:34:02,582 --> 00:34:04,959
I just wanna ask you one question.

401
00:34:05,168 --> 00:34:07,878
You've been a naughty guy,
haven't you?

402
00:34:08,129 --> 00:34:09,546
Come on, admit it now.

403
00:34:09,714 --> 00:34:12,216
You've been just a little bit naughty,
haven't you?

404
00:34:12,467 --> 00:34:15,219
- I was kind of...
- That's all right. I understand.

405
00:34:15,387 --> 00:34:18,597
I can... What do
the young folks say today?

406
00:34:18,807 --> 00:34:21,475
"Dig where you're
coming from, brother".

407
00:34:21,685 --> 00:34:24,520
- You wanna be rich, right?
- How, wha...

408
00:34:24,729 --> 00:34:28,232
I was born rich. Never worn
the same pair of socks twice.

409
00:34:28,400 --> 00:34:29,900
What do you do with your socks?

410
00:34:30,151 --> 00:34:34,029
I don't know. They're laundered and sent
to some charitable institution, I think.

411
00:34:34,239 --> 00:34:37,408
Actually, I don't know.
Maybe they turn them into dust rags...

412
00:34:37,617 --> 00:34:39,076
or pen-wipers or something.

413
00:34:39,244 --> 00:34:40,911
Or maybe socks.

414
00:34:41,121 --> 00:34:43,872
Yes! That never occurred to me.

415
00:34:44,082 --> 00:34:47,876
Gus, you know something?
You're a genius.

416
00:34:48,128 --> 00:34:51,755
A naughty genius, but what the hell?
Nobody's perfect, right? Cheers.

417
00:34:51,923 --> 00:34:54,925
Because of the half-cent thing
with the computers.

418
00:34:55,176 --> 00:34:58,095
No, no, because computers
rule the world today.

419
00:34:58,263 --> 00:35:01,932
The fellow that can fool the computers
can rule the world himself.

420
00:35:02,934 --> 00:35:06,437
I've been searching for somebody
who can make these machines...

421
00:35:06,604 --> 00:35:08,939
do what they're not supposed to.
Get my drift?

422
00:35:09,357 --> 00:35:11,066
- Yes!
- Gus...

423
00:35:11,234 --> 00:35:16,030
Webscoe, the Webscoe industrial
complex, is a family-owned cartel.

424
00:35:16,239 --> 00:35:18,115
Some magnesium here,
some zinc there.

425
00:35:18,283 --> 00:35:20,284
Railroads, farm machinery.
You follow me?

426
00:35:20,452 --> 00:35:21,952
I follow you, sir.

427
00:35:22,162 --> 00:35:24,288
- Gus, do you know what I want now?
- No.

428
00:35:24,456 --> 00:35:25,539
I want coffee.

429
00:35:25,707 --> 00:35:27,458
All right. Black, cream, sugar, or?

430
00:35:27,667 --> 00:35:29,710
No, you don't seem to understand.

431
00:35:29,919 --> 00:35:33,297
Under different company names,
I control the price of coffee beans...

432
00:35:33,548 --> 00:35:37,676
in Venezuela, Brazil, Bolivia,
Jamaica and the Republic of Gabon.

433
00:35:37,886 --> 00:35:41,638
But I've got a problem and I think
maybe you can help me.

434
00:35:41,806 --> 00:35:45,809
One country won't play ball with me.
You know how that can bug a guy, right?

435
00:35:45,977 --> 00:35:48,312
That could bug... What country?

436
00:35:49,689 --> 00:35:51,940
- Colombia.
- Colombia?

437
00:35:52,108 --> 00:35:55,110
Colombia has two important exports,
and one of them's coffee.

438
00:35:55,320 --> 00:35:58,947
And I've tried to reason with them.
Believe me, I've tried.

439
00:35:59,157 --> 00:36:02,284
But this one miserable,
pissant little country...

440
00:36:02,494 --> 00:36:07,831
has the gall to think it can dictate
the economy of an open market. Gus.

441
00:36:08,333 --> 00:36:10,667
Gus, my friend...

442
00:36:11,503 --> 00:36:14,296
we're going to teach them
a lesson, aren't we?

443
00:36:15,340 --> 00:36:18,175
Destroy the entire
Colombian coffee crop...

444
00:36:18,343 --> 00:36:20,844
right down to the last bean.

445
00:36:21,012 --> 00:36:23,305
- The last bean, we are.
- Right.

446
00:36:23,515 --> 00:36:26,850
But you got so much. You know, like...

447
00:36:27,018 --> 00:36:29,728
A wise man once said,
I think it was Attila the Hun...

448
00:36:29,938 --> 00:36:32,523
"It is not enough that I succeed.

449
00:36:32,732 --> 00:36:35,692
Everyone else must fail".

450
00:36:35,944 --> 00:36:37,444
Seems fair.

451
00:36:37,737 --> 00:36:39,196
- Gus.
- What?

452
00:36:39,364 --> 00:36:43,033
You are going to do this for me.

453
00:36:45,662 --> 00:36:47,830
- How?
- The weather.

454
00:36:48,540 --> 00:36:50,207
You didn't say your mother was here.

455
00:36:50,375 --> 00:36:53,377
I'm his sister. His baby sister.

456
00:36:53,545 --> 00:36:56,547
Gus, tell me, have you ever
heard of Vulcan?

457
00:36:56,881 --> 00:36:58,215
Hi, Ms. Vulcan.

458
00:36:58,383 --> 00:37:01,176
Vulcan is the weather satellite
our government put up...

459
00:37:01,386 --> 00:37:02,719
to monitor the weather.

460
00:37:02,887 --> 00:37:07,182
But if somebody were to reprogram it,
it could do much more.

461
00:37:07,392 --> 00:37:09,017
It could make weather.

462
00:37:09,185 --> 00:37:10,727
Storms and floods.

463
00:37:10,895 --> 00:37:12,688
Blizzards, heat waves.

464
00:37:12,897 --> 00:37:14,064
How do you do that?

465
00:37:14,482 --> 00:37:17,734
Like everything else
in the 20th century, Gus.

466
00:37:17,902 --> 00:37:19,403
You push buttons.

467
00:37:21,072 --> 00:37:24,283
- There you go.
- It's the first time I won anything.

468
00:37:24,492 --> 00:37:25,742
You won my hand, Maury.

469
00:37:25,910 --> 00:37:28,745
But this is the first time
I won anything valuable.

470
00:37:28,913 --> 00:37:30,581
Let's get one with the sombreros.

471
00:37:30,790 --> 00:37:34,084
Mr. White, you'll be in this,
handing them their plane tickets.

472
00:37:34,294 --> 00:37:36,753
- Why do I have to do this?
- Why do I have to do this?

473
00:37:36,921 --> 00:37:40,257
You're lucky I didn't fire you.
I get a chance at exclusive photos...

474
00:37:40,425 --> 00:37:42,259
of history's biggest factory fire.

475
00:37:42,427 --> 00:37:45,262
He comes home with a broken leg
and 12 melted rolls of film.

476
00:37:45,430 --> 00:37:46,763
It was hot.

477
00:37:46,931 --> 00:37:49,099
Smile, Mr. White.

478
00:37:50,101 --> 00:37:52,686
South America!
I can't believe my luck!

479
00:37:53,188 --> 00:37:56,106
See, if you don't want them
to trace it back...

480
00:37:56,316 --> 00:37:59,443
you've gotta punch in
to some little rinky-dink outfit...

481
00:37:59,611 --> 00:38:02,070
that has a little
Mickey Mouse computer...

482
00:38:02,280 --> 00:38:05,240
Someplace you can sneak into, right?

483
00:38:05,450 --> 00:38:06,617
Somebody could...

484
00:38:06,826 --> 00:38:10,829
